WEBVTT

1
00:00:01,500 --> 00:00:09,000
Dr. Rivera: Good to see you both. Let's hear what came up in practice. What did you notice?

2
00:00:10,800 --> 00:00:27,300
Participant A: This week I actually managed to stay with the sensation a lot more. I kept bringing my attention back every time it drifted. It still hurt but I noticed I wasn't fighting it the same way — I was just kind of with it.

3
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:40,500
Dr. Rivera: That's a really important observation. Staying with discomfort without fighting it — that IS the practice. You're building a different relationship with the pain signal.

4
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:57,800
Participant B: I noticed something weird. When the pain got bad at work I started to get really anxious about it, and then I caught myself — like I could see the anxiety as a separate thing from the pain. I was watching myself get anxious. It was strange.

5
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:10,200
Dr. Rivera: What you're describing — watching your own mental process from a step back — that's metacognition. That's a significant shift. How did that feel in the moment?

6
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:22,500
Participant B: Kind of a relief actually. Like the anxiety didn't own me the way it usually does. I could see it happening and just let it be there.

7
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:35,000
Dr. Rivera: Exactly. When you can observe a mental event you're no longer fully fused with it. The mind wanders and reacts — that's how attention works. Noticing that loop is what changes it.

8
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:52,400
Participant A: I had something similar. I was in a lot of pain during the weekend but instead of catastrophizing I just kept asking myself, what is actually happening right now in my body? And I noticed the pain was not one thing. It kept shifting — dull here, sharp there, then gone briefly.

9
00:01:54,000 --> 00:02:05,000
Dr. Rivera: That's very close to reappraisal — seeing through the label "pain" to the actual texture of sensation. How might you bring that lens to your practice this coming week?

10
00:02:06,500 --> 00:02:18,000
Participant A: I want to keep asking that question. Not just what does it feel like in general but what exactly is happening right now, in detail.

11
00:02:19,500 --> 00:02:30,000
Dr. Rivera: That detailed, curious attention is the core skill. Participant B, how will you use the observer stance you found this week?

12
00:02:31,500 --> 00:02:44,000
Participant B: I'm going to try to name what I notice. Like say to myself, there is anxiety, there is tension — give it a label so I don't get swept up in it.

13
00:02:45,500 --> 00:02:54,000
Dr. Rivera: Labeling is a powerful anchor. Great work this week. You're both moving in a meaningful direction.

